english:
  title: Epitaph of Master Guan the Recluse
  author: Kim Il-son
  language: eng
  text: 'The recluse''s name was Shu, styled Shu-gu. His original surname was Mao. The Mao Prefect and the Marquis of Guancheng Mao Yuanrui were both his ancestors. The Mao clan''s founder became renowned since the time writing was invented. He assisted Fuxi in drawing the Eight Trigrams, followed Confucius in editing the Spring and Autumn Annals, and when the auspicious unicorn was captured, the line was cut off in Lu. His descendants scattered to serve various lords—those in Chu were called Mao Shuai, those in Yan called Mao Fu, those in Wu called Mao Bulü, and those in Qin called Mao Bi. When Qin unified the Six States, the Mao elsewhere lost their prominence, while only those in Qin remained illustrious, continuing so to this day. Descendants inherited their ancestors'' names unchanged—such is the way of foreign peoples. At first he held the post of clerk in General Meng''s household and was greatly favored, recommended to the First Emperor, and enfeoffed in Guancheng. However, since Qin organized the world into prefectures and counties with no actual division of lands, those who say the Mao became prominent through Meng''s recommendation are mistaken. Following Li Si, he became skilled in seal script and clerical script, escaping the disaster of Lu Sheng. In the late Han, he was placed in a golden house and cherished like A-jiao, adorned with ivory ornaments and precious pearls. His extravagance nearly ruined him, but his wide usefulness saved him. In the Wei and Jin period, he moved between the households of Zhong Yao and Wang Xizhi as a retainer. The Right General''s fame rose through him, yet disliked his excess and wrote a Manual to restrain it. Later in the houses of both the Greater and Lesser Ouyang, he remained unrepentant. Yet his regulation depends on those above. The Simplified Emperor of Liang specially prepared a seat, honoring him like Xu Ru, with dust thick upon it—yet he dared not be careless. He also served the Prince of Xiangdong in writing books, and the prince divided him into three ranks, appointing him with gold and silver fish pouches for loyalty and filial piety, silver for virtue and conduct, bamboo tallies for literary composition. All drafts received his seal. The Mao lineage controlled the written word through generations. In later times, those who dreamed of his strangeness found their writing advanced. He once presented five-colored inspiration to Jiang Yan, and blue-green tubes to Ji Shaoyu and others—none without verification. Yet since Qin, official histories lost his name. In the Tang, there was Mao Hua, who had spiritual communion with Li Bai. Vain of his beauty, he indulged in women without restraint. Once accompanying Li Bai at court, when the Xuanzong summoned ten palace attendants and froze the inkstone, he had them all blow upon it with their mouths. While the attendants held still by imperial command, the emperor merely watched without remark, and Li Bai offered no apology for recommending an unsuitable person. Yet he knew the importance of fundamentals, often laboring in fields alongside Wang Bo. The Mao''s presence in the world is not of a single day—through all ages lords and ministers showed thin favor, extracting their strength when young, abandoning them to gutters when old. Only the Buddhist monk Zhiyong first extended compassion, collecting and burying them. The Mao lineage comes not from one source alone, many produced in Fanyu. Their origin resembles the Rong barbarians—their ancestors were all of foul and base kind: some were goats, some tigers, some apes, some chickens and ducks, some foxes, some rats and hares. Conceived in daylight with men, they gradually refined and entered the Middle Kingdom, all becoming Mao clan. They abandoned felt and furs, favoring lands of culture and learning, and gentlemen praised them, using them without regard to lineage. Yet by nature they followed others, caring not for wisdom or folly, craft or clumsiness—taking only what tasks were assigned without demurral. They never presumed with wealth or lorded over the poor; though slaves, if lettered they would serve. Their talents were great—the mysteries of heaven''s way and human nature, the ancient scripts of tadpole and seal—all could they render with subtle curve and twist. Yet never establishing their own doctrine, always serving others, they were thereby despised, called "sharp-headed slaves." In Northern Wei there was Gu Bi, also a barbarian with pointed head, called "Brush Sir." When Fuli set out to hunt, Bi as garrison commander offered a weak horse, enraging Fuli: "Sharp-headed slave! Dare you measure me? When I return to the capital, I shall have you put to death!" Yet through his uprightness he was not slain, and later receiving kindness from Yang Wende, Fuli recorded his merit without adding punishment. When Fuli died, Bi was implicated by law and executed. Yet Northern Wei law, favoring ancient ways and abhorring Han cruelty, did not practice extermination, so his descendants survived. Serving Tang when Taizong had already pacified all under heaven yet still glorified arms, he was much displeased. When Taizong had him learn spear technique, he utterly refused, befriending Yu Shinan who urged him until they both appeared before the throne. He followed Liu Gongquan in direct remonstrance and gained some praise. Yet since the Mao dislike warriors, warriors dislike the Mao in return. Shu-gu''s five-generations-ancestor Zui was rejected by Shi Honzhao, himself a warrior. Governing in an immoral age, he dismissed the worthy so—one can understand the times thereby. Initially when Taizong wished to adopt and give the imperial surname to captives, in its decline when eunuchs controlled armies, raising strong men as their heart and ministers of domain mimicked them, it became custom. By Five Dynasties no ruler was exempt. Thus even heroes and bold men, gradually infected, abandoned their lineages and assumed false surnames, thinking nothing strange of it. In early Liang, a cadet branch of Mao fled central disorder and served Southern Tang. When Li Bian compiled genealogies, they participated, adopting the Wu King as ancestor, soon thereafter changing their surname to Guan, falsely claiming descent from Guan Zhong. Though their forebears were illustrious, they lacked the praise given the sage—Guan Zhong was called benevolent, so they seized this to boast to men. Later Guo Chongzhao emulated this, bowing at Guo Ziyi''s tomb and making him his ancestor. The world had reached such a state—human relationships destroyed. When Guan''s descendants entered Song, seeing that Di Qing did not claim Di Renjie as ancestor, they were ashamed and could not compose themselves. Their friend Chen Xuan explained: "The Cang, Ku, Sima, and Sikong surnames all derived from offices. Your ancestor was enfeoffed at Guancheng—what harm in taking Guan as surname?" Guan was pleased. Fortunately, the sage ministers of Song, though not readily receiving strangers, hurried to welcome the Guan clan, fearing to lag behind, displaying their virtue and literary works. Sima Guang especially revered them, wearing yellow robes without considering it presumption—surely accounting for their joint compilation of the Zizhi Tongjian, whose merit reaches ten thousand generations. Yet their old habits persisted: Su Shi''s satirized "fat-skinned trowel-head" and Zhu Xi''s close examination of "date-pit shape" were neither Guan-born, and in later degeneration became craftsmen''s descendants, their baseness deepened. Only in Shu Jing''s house, admiring Kongming, they claimed Zhuge descent, the world calling Zhuge-born most noble, greatly praised by Su Zi. Guan naturally loves movement—movement shortens life, stillness slightly extends it, yet prolonged stasis breeds illness. The Su learned from Li Jianzhong''s method: one cash of mercury boiled in hot water made into paste, given to Guan for miraculous effect. The Guan clan long in the East—their fortune rises and falls with ages, their preferences varying. Some pig-line descendants became stewards to Mongol princesses, bearing cauldron and chopping-block to Goryeo, their great-grandsons like Hai-sheng so tall as a beam, walking high and speaking loudly, unsuited to the times, without peer, only befriending the prodigy Pak Neul, their traces strange. Beyond these, only four lines most flourish, all taking Guan as surname. The marten-crest line noble, the lamb-fur line base, the Mao-line between. Their kind prone to shortness and breakage, disdained, though claiming descent from spirits—like iron-furnace steps. The marten and lamb lines live somewhat longer and sturdy-healthy, pleasing people, much employed. Bearing central earth''s yellow-brown color, the kingdom uniformly calls them "Guan-son" without naming them, yet unclear their origin. Some suspect the yellow-bristled of the Geling Records, steward of Reed-gate fortress, later serving Goryeo. When Song''s Qian Mufu returned from embassy, bringing him along, the imperial historian saw and loved him, disliking the foreign surname matching his own, calling him "ape-kind" in verse. Never knowing it was not Yellow-surname, and Goryeo truly had no ape-kind—what Mufu obtained was today''s yellow-robes. Or it is said the yellow-crest''s ancestor named Youo was skilled at tree-climbing like wood-spirits, or named Shou wearing red-yellow robes—Shou and xing similar-sounding, thus confused. Unclear if true. There was also a short fellow surnamed Jia-zi, beautiful-bearded, useable for tasks, yet cunning in tunneling, stealing much from the great granary—dismissed on theft charges. Broadly, Guan by nature are greedy-corrupt. Shu-gu, yellow-crest line, wearing Daoist robes, outwardly admiring purity. His father named Wei-sheng, rash and vicious, called "yellow-wild son." Multiple times enfeoffed as Marquis of Zhushan, dying in discussion at the Fengshang office. "Receiving favor from another and accomplishing tasks" called Xiang; "greed destroying office" called Mo—thus he received the posthumous name Marquis Xiang-Mo. Shu-gu was angered, wishing to petition following some families'' example to clear it, but seeing that family''s son could not gain the request, he ceased. Thinking to himself: being of slave-barbarian lineage, honored and prominent for generations, he carried this burden, creating mocking and satirical words written in records—fearing one day the book-burning and scholar-burying catastrophe would recur. Thus he refused office, seeking pure-white scholars to befriend, dwelling with me in one room long. Not yet having tried the mercury method, fearing his illness might strike, I brought him to the study hall. Shu-gu in youth had sharp spirit yet calm temperament, disliking activity, constantly requesting to remove his cap and retire—I would not permit it. Though given tasks, he would not fully exert himself, yet his rice-jar frequently emptied. Without this he could not support himself alone. Though good at gathering, he never kept for himself, promptly sharing all with his friend Zhu-sheng without remainder. Yet his own person bore deep pollution—I know the Guan''s poverty was not from greed. Later seeing Wen-zhong Gong''s posthumous name corrected, Shu-gu sighed: "Good and evil change with people, preference can alter—what lasts a hundred generations is but empty words." He regretted not petitioning to correct Xiang-Mo. At first seeing his brothers, some had intention, some had none. I chose the none-intentioned, whose heart had no second direction, calling him "No-mind son," playing with him—this was Shu-gu himself. In conduct withdrawn and silent, yet meeting understanding friends, his brilliance could not be contained. Shu-gu suffered lung ailment throughout life, loving to drink water, bathing and playing as a swimming child, ducking head into pool, submerging and emerging without rest. In writing, words flowed without cessation. When cold weather came and he drank much water, his belly swelled greatly. I feared he would freeze to death, hastily bringing him to the fire—yet hot and cold struck together, unbearable, sweating and collapsing to ground, he could not rise. His attendants lifted to bathe him, his head stripped bare with nothing to comb. This was from brooding on the past and sorrowing for the age, emotion showing in speech, his hair early thinned—sorrowful indeed. So we placed a bamboo-skin crown upon him and wrapped him in paper quilting, following his lifelong intent. Alas! From birth my servant, sparing no strength, always shaking his head at worldly affairs yet unable to leave me, illness preventing him from completing his years. How could I not grieve? Human life''s full span is a hundred years, yet deemed short. His clan''s full span barely a year, Shu-gu but half—why does the Creator prove so stingy? Such wisdom as Shu-gu''s the world rarely finds. When I had chanted verses unspoken, he anticipated my meaning as if mirrors reflecting liver and gall, insisting on revealing my innermost feelings before ceasing. Now it is done. His clan, though spreading across the land, each bound to their own master, cannot support each other. Five brothers all discord. Those he long befriended mostly common folk, whom the world calls "dead friends"—like Zhu Zhibai and Yi Xuanguang, pretending not to know each other. Zhibai especially ungrateful; Shi Xuzhong peculiarly unmoved. Shu-gu unmarried had no sons; his corpse on the mat with none to collect it—my sorrow deepened. Consulting my bed-mate Jiang Muxi, we took the precedent of Zhu Wenzhong, Tao Jingjie, and Zhengyao Xiansheng, privately granting the posthumous name "Cultured and Sorrowful Recluse," using my stipend to purchase a coffin from the Return-to-Virtue Bureau, burying him at the northern slope of the Reading Hall. No outer coffin, no earthen mound—matching ancient practice. The Guan clan so numerous, fearing later generations lose the genealogy, and since Shu-gu had lamented to me: "Zhiyong has a tomb but no epitaph; Han Yu has a biography but no inscription"—I write epitaph and compose this inscription, burning it into brick and burying together to comfort him in the unseen realm. The inscription says: "In the year Gui-chou, the month of winter solstice, at Longshan''s foot, behind the Reading Hall''s old site, one handful of earth—here rests Guan Shu-gu."'
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This epitaph is an extended allegory using the brush (毛筆) as its subject, personified throughout the text as a member of the Guan clan. The genealogy, historical references, and biographical details all serve as metaphorical commentary on the nature, uses, and social position of brushes in Chinese civilization.
  - key: ''
    value: The names "Mao the Prefect" and "Marquis of Guancheng Mao Yuanrui" are both alternative names for the brush, derived from its historical associations and functions.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to "iron-furnace steps" comes from Liu Zihou's essay on a place that retained its name even after ceasing to function, used here to describe lineages that persist in name alone after losing substance.
